observations.recommendation:
We reiterated the following
recommendation:
 Re-assess the viability of PPAs, and fast-track its implementation to warrant delivery of benefits to the intended beneficiaries. Otherwise, return the funds to the respective source agency for other resources that could be put to better use by other agencies needing assistance;
 return the unexpended balance of completed projects to the respective source agencies;
 submit to the Audit Team the corresponding liquidation report and other pertinent documents for post-audit and issuance of appropriate credit notice; and
 exert effort to trace the source of the forwarded balances and unaccounted balances for fair presentation in the financial statement.

We recommended the following to management:
 Management should use the Statement of Work Accomplished (SWA) in the computation of the payment to the contractor;
 Exercise due care in the preparation of documents;
 Documentary stamp taxes should not be included in the computation of the payment to the contractor;
Use uniform rates in the computation of taxes withheld;
The total cumulative accomplishment less previous payment and taxes should be presented on the face of the disbursement voucher;
The amounts presented in the disbursement voucher should be the same with the amounts recorded in the Journals; and
Avoid tampering of documents submitted by the contractor.

In view of the above observations, we have recommended the following:

The Municipal Accountant:
issue demand letters to the accountable officers to liquidate their   cash advances and refund any unused amount;
record advances as liquidated only upon submission of complete documents;
immediately submit to the Audit Team the liquidation documents of the ₱112,300.00 cash advances of the Municipal Treasurer; and
not allow additional cash advance to be granted to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given to him/her is first settled; 
the Municipal Mayor consider initiating the withholding of salaries of accountable officers who fail to comply with the demand letters issued; and
henceforth, the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances should be made in accordance with the law.

In view of the foregoing observations, we have recommended the following;

That management ensure the immediate completion of the on-going projects which have already incurred significant delays;
Require the Municipal Engineer to conduct regular monitoring and supervision of projects to ensure that infrastructure projects are accomplished in accordance with the terms of the contract and to document the same and to impose liquidated damages and other appropriate sanctions, as maybe justified; and
Submit the pertinent documents for proper validation and evaluation.

In view of the noted deficiencies, we have  recommended the following:

that the Municipal Mayor instruct the department heads to prepare their respective PPMPs to be consolidated by the BAC into an Annual Procurement Plan of the Agency;  
that the Municipal Budget Officer see to it that the Annual Procurement Plan is consistent with their duly approved yearly budget.  He should also accomplish the Obligation Request properly which shall be the basis of recording obligations in the registries  and that he should maintain RAAOs to facilitate monitoring of expenses and balances of appropriations, prevent the incurrence of expenditures in excess of allotments and shall be the basis of preparing the Statement of Appropriations, Allotments, Obligations and Balances; 
that the agency takes into consideration the existence of appropriation before incurring expenditures in conformity with rules and regulations;
that expenses be limited to the amount provided in the budget to ensure the implementation of other programs and projects of the Municipality; and
as to the travels, the agency head should implement a more stringent policy such as but not limited to determining attendees by the required participants per letter/invitation on seminars/training/conventions; and the Municipal Accountant should require the original and clean copies of certificate of appearance/other necessary supporting papers.

In view of the above audit observations, we recommend the following:

That management maintain a special book of account and depository account for the share from Tobacco Excise Tax;
That management ensure that the programs, projects and activities to be undertaken are duly included in the Annual Investment Plan of the Municipality;
That management submit the required documents to facilitate monitoring and evaluation of the projects and comply with the implementing rules and regulations of RA 9184 (Government Procurement Reform Act);
That the Obligation Request attached to the voucher be properly accomplished indicating therein the funding source of the disbursement;
That a separate Registry of Allotment and Obligations for the fund from RA 7171 be maintained for proper control; and 
That a supplemental budget or appropriation ordinance for the municipality’s share from the tobacco excise tax be prepared and approved by the Sanggunian Bayan before disbursements will be made.

We have recommended the following:

that management submit a copy of the duly approved APP that includes procurement for goods and infrastructure projects. Henceforth, an APP should be prepared and approved before undertaking any procurement and should be duly submitted for review and verification;
that management submit the missing documentations as stated in the foregoing discussions.  Henceforth, complete bidding documents should be submitted on time for COA evaluation and review;
that the BAC observe the required pre-procurement conference for infrastructure project with an ABC above ₱5 million to ensure, among others, that the procurement is in accordance with the project and annual procurement plans and to determine the readiness of the agency for the procurement at hand;
that the BAC, through its BAC Secretariat, observe the proper advertising and posting of the Invitation to Bid as prescribed in the Revised IRR of RA 9184 to encourage more participants in the bidding process and intensify the competition among them, which in turn, will ensure that the LGU will get the best possible proposals, as to quality and cost, for the project sought to be procured. The Municipality should have a specific prominent and public place reserved for posting of the Invitation to Bid such as bulletin board in the municipal hall;
that the BAC invite at least three (3) observers to attend in all stages of the procurement process to promote transparency and ensure that bidding is existent in the procurement activities of the agency as provided in Section 13 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184;
that the Municipality ensure that all the documentary requirements are complied with before entering into contract with the winning bidder;
that the BAC, through the BAC Secretariat, post the Notice of Award and Notice to Proceed in the PhilGEPS to promote transparency and efficiency in the conduct of procurement procedures; and
that the BAC strictly comply with the provisions of RA 9184 in the conduct of public bidding and awarding of contracts/projects. BAC members, BAC secretariat and the TWG should familiarize themselves with the different rules and regulations set forth by RA 9184. Clear and readable documents and lacking documents should be submitted for COA evaluation and review.

The Municipality did not submit the monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF in violation of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012 precluding a timely review of the transactions.

Unexpended LDRRMF for the year 2015 amounting to ₱625,858.49 was not transferred to a special trust fund account in violation of Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1 and COA Circular No. 2012-002.

In view of the above observations, we have recommended the following:

that the Municipal Mayor instruct the MDRRMO  to submit the monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF using the format in accordance with COA Circular 2012-002, to facilitate the monitoring and evaluation of the accomplishments and disbursement of the fund;
that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer to transfer the balance of ₱625,858.49 to the separate depository account for LDRRMF; 
that the unexpended balance of QRF of ₱180,152.19 should not be used to other programs/activities;
that the  transferred unexpended balance of year 2013 and 2014 should be reclassified as Trust Liability –DRRM account for fair presentation in the financial statements;
that a separate LDRRMF Investment Plan should be prepared for the unutilized balance of the LDRRMF and should be utilized in accordance with pertinent laws, rules and regulations; and 
that the Municipal Accountant should see to it that all claims  are fully supported with the required documentation provided under COA Circular No. 2012-001 before payments are made.

We have recommended that the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer:
Record the audit adjustments in the treasury books to correct the erroneous recording of the current year’s transactions;
Reconcile monthly the accounting with the treasury records pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002 to immediately detect errors and prove the correctness and accuracy of their records;
Deposit  all collections promptly and intact with the authorized government bank, in compliance with  Section 32 of the NGAs Manual Volume I to avoid  possible loss and misuse of funds; and
Trace back transactions before year 2013 to account for the un-reconciled discrepancy.

In view of the noted lapses we have recommended that the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer:
ensure timely preparation and submission of the bank reconciliation statements;
analyze the reconciling items identified and make necessary adjustments pertaining thereto;
exert extra effort to review the outstanding/stale/cancelled checks; and
require the Municipal Treasurer to cancel the unclaimed stale checks and furnish the Accountant with the original DV’s and its supporting documents for the preparation of the JEV.

We have reiterated to recommend the following:
reassess the viability of PPAs, and fast-track its implementation to warrant delivery of benefits to the intended beneficiaries. Otherwise, return the funds to the respective source agency for other resources that could be put to better use by other agencies needing assistance;
return the unexpended balance of completed  projects to the respective source agencies;
submit to the Audit Team the corresponding liquidation report and other pertinent documents for post-audit and issuance of appropriate credit notice; and
re-classify the proper account for the fund received from STL and make the necessary adjustments.

In view of the above noted deficiencies, we have recommended the following:
that management identify priority projects to be funded under the 20% development fund with sufficient details  and particulars. Guidelines and policies involving the implementation of these programs/projects should be considered and included in the planning and budgeting stage;
submit the Program of Works as supporting documents to the Annual Investment Plan to aid in the further analysis of funded projects vis-à-vis actual expenditures;
that management implement only projects set forth in the Annual Investment Plan. In instances where other priority projects are identified for implementation, a Sangguniang Bayan resolution first be passed for the realignment and revision of the Annual Investment Plan to be submitted for approval by the Sangguniang Panlalawigan;
submit the SB resolution for the realignment of the BUB 2016 Counterpart amounting to ₱152,500.00;
that management strictly follow the guidelines laid out under DBM-DILG Joint Circular 2017-1 and include in its 20% Municipal Development Plan only projects that are permanent in nature and shall be fully utilized that yields greater benefit to the people; and
that management require the Municipal Treasurer to transfer all amounts allotted for the 20% development fund to the depository account specifically created for such fund and the Municipal Accountant to maintain separate books and subsidiary ledgers for easier monitoring of utilization and to avoid misuse of funds.
Management comment:
The municipal accountant submitted some of the noted lacking documents for the above transactions on May 11, 2018.
Auditor’s Rejoinder:
The audit team observed that the additional documents submitted lack necessary information such as dates of Statement of Work Accomplished, Inspection Report, Project Accomplishment Report and Progress Billing.
